reviews.review_text: the stadium never moved like this... This show sticks out to me because of the unusuall high voltage in the guitars on this night...can you think of a better show opener than a mind-blowin` Shakedown that seemed to jam forever.Wang-Dang was next and it was on from there.Jack-a-Roe was unbelievable.Bobby then proceded over and got to some roots with an acustic Mama Tried >Mexicali Blues deuo...then the absolutly best Loose Lucy my ears had the priviledge of hearing.Picasso Moon took us to break....the audience at full attention Phil muttered out a great rendition of Box of Rain to get us groovin` again.Sampson>Ship of Fools>Rollin`Tumblin` right into Samba,thats jamming at its best.Wharf Rat eased out of space into one of the longest NFA ever.the night ended with a beautiful Brokedown Palace,what ashow..we miss you Jerry

Depressing agswst33 - you have got to be kidding me. I wish I was on the same drugs as you. I had decent seats in the lower section on the side, and could hardly hear Garcia. This show, despite the nice setlist, was terrible, mainly because Jerry was slumped in the shadows, barely playing, going through the motions being carried by the rest of the band. His voice sounded horrible when he croaked out Rollin and Tumblin. The only show I ever wanted to leave during the show. Sad. Two stars only because the rest of the band and Hornsby were trying to raise the sail.

great tape; very good show This, and the night before, distinguish themselves for summer 1995 by being really good shows.  (Albany certainly had its moments, too.) Jerry's fingers were working mighty fine.  Having Bruce back on the piano certainly helps, too.

Excellent recording!
